# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autoit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autoit/autoit] The scripting language in AutoIt 1 and 2 was statement-driven and designed primarily for simulating user interaction.
[src:autoit/autoit] From version 3 onward, the AutoIt syntax is similar to that found in the BASIC family of languages.
[src:autoit/autoit] In this form, AutoIt is a general-purpose, third-generation programming language with a classical data model and a variant data type that can store several types of data, including arrays.
[src:autoit/autoit] An AutoIt automation script can be converted into a compressed, stand-alone executable which can be run on computers even if they do not have the AutoIt interpreter installed.
[src:autoit/autoit] A wide range of function libraries (known as UDFs, or "User Defined Functions") are also included as standard or are available from the website to add specialized functionality.
[src:autoit/autoit] AutoIt is also distributed with an IDE based on the free SciTE editor.
[src:autoit/autoit] The compiler and help text are fully integrated and provide a *de facto* standard environment for developers using AutoIt.
[src:autoit/autoit] AutoIt1 and AutoIt2 were closed-source projects, and had a very different syntax than AutoIt3, whose syntax is more like VBScript and BASIC.
[src:autoit/autoit] AutoIt3 was initially free and open-source, licensed under the terms of the GNU General Public License, with its initial public release 3.0.100 in February 2004, and had open-source releases in March 2004 and August 2004.
[src:autoit/autoit] Version 3.0.102, released in August 2004, was initially open-source, but by January 2005 was distributed as closed-source.
[src:autoit/autoit] Subsequent releases, starting from the February 2005 release of version 3.1.0, were all closed-source.
[src:autoit/autoit] The free and open-source AutoHotkey project derived 29 of its functions from the AutoIt 3.1 source code.
[src:autoit/autoit] The AutoHotkey syntax is quite different from AutoIt3 syntax, and rather resembles AutoIt2 syntax.
[src:autoit/autoit] AutoIt is typically used to produce utility software for Microsoft Windows and to automate routine tasks, such as systems management, monitoring, maintenance, or software installation.
[src:autoit/autoit] It is also used to simulate user interaction, whereby an application is "driven" (via automated form entry, keypresses, mouse clicks, and so on) to do things by an AutoIt script.
[src:autoit/autoit] AutoIt can also be used in low-cost laboratory automation.
[src:autoit/autoit] Applications include instrument synchronization, alarm monitoring and results gathering.
[src:autoit/autoit] Devices such as CNC routers and 3D-printers can also be controlled.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:autoit/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:autoit/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:autoit/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:autoit/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:autoit/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:autoit/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:autoit/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:autoit/expect] Expect is used to automate control of interactive applications such as Telnet, FTP, passwd, fsck, rlogin, tip, SSH, and others.
[src:autoit/expect] Expect uses pseudo terminals (Unix) or emulates a console (Windows), starts the target program, and then communicates with it, just as a human would, via the terminal or console interface.
[src:autoit/expect] Tk, another Tcl extension, can be used to provide a GUI.
[src:autoit/expect] Expect serves as a "glue" to link existing utilities together.
[src:autoit/expect] The general idea is to figure out how to make Expect use the system's existing tools rather than figure out how to solve a problem inside of Expect.
[src:autoit/expect] A key usage of Expect involves commercial software products.
[src:autoit/expect] Many of these products provide some type of command-line interface, but these usually lack the power needed to write scripts.
[src:autoit/expect] They were built to service the users administering the product, but the company often does not spend the resources to fully implement a robust scripting language.
[src:autoit/expect] An Expect script can spawn a shell, look up environmental variables, perform some Unix commands to retrieve more information, and then enter into the product's command-line interface armed with the necessary information to achieve the user's goal.
[src:autoit/expect] After retrieving information by interacting with the product via its command-line interface, the script can make intelligent decisions about what action to take, if any.
[src:autoit/expect] Every time an Expect operation is completed, the results are stored in a local variable called $expect_out.
[src:autoit/expect] This allows the script to harvest information to feedback to the user, and it also allows conditional behavior of what to send next based on the circumstances.
[src:autoit/expect] A common use of Expect is to set up a testing suite for programs, utilities or embedded systems.
[src:autoit/expect] DejaGnu is a testing suite written using Expect for use in testing.
[src:autoit/expect] It has been used for testing GCC and remote targets such as embedded development.
[src:autoit/expect] Expect script can be automated using a tool called 'autoexpect'.
[src:autoit/expect] This tool observes your actions and generates an Expect script using heuristics.
[src:autoit/expect] Though generated code may be large and somewhat cryptic, one can always tweak the generated script to get the exact code.
[src:autoit/expect] Using passwords as command-line arguments, like in this example, is a huge security hole, as any other user on the machine can read this password by running "ps".
[src:autoit/expect] You can, however, add code that will prompt you for your password rather than giving your password as an argument.
[src:autoit/expect] Various projects implement Expect-like functionality in other languages, such as C#, Java, Scala, Groovy, Perl, Python, Ruby, Shell and Go.
[src:autoit/expect] These are generally not exact clones of the original Expect, but the concepts tend to be very similar.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] In software engineering, **graphical user interface testing** is the process of testing a product's graphical user interface (GUI) to ensure it meets its specifications.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This is normally done through the use of a variety of test cases.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] To generate a set of test cases, test designers attempt to cover all the functionality of the system and fully exercise the GUI itself.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The difficulty in accomplishing this task is twofold: to deal with domain size and sequences.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] In addition, the tester faces more difficulty when they have to do regression testing.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Unlike a CLI (command-line interface) system, a GUI may have additional operations that need to be tested.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] A relatively small program such as Microsoft WordPad has 325 possible GUI operations.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] In a large program, the number of operations can easily be an order of magnitude larger.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The second problem is the sequencing problem.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Some functionality of the system may only be accomplished with a sequence of GUI events.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] For example, to open a file a user may first have to click on the File Menu, then select the Open operation, use a dialog box to specify the file name, and focus the application on the newly opened window.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Increasing the number of possible operations increases the sequencing problem exponentially.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This can become a serious issue when the tester is creating test cases manually.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Regression testing is often a challenge with GUIs as well.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] A GUI may change significantly, even though the underlying application does not.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] A test designed to follow a certain path through the GUI may then fail since a button, menu item, or dialog may have changed location or appearance.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] These issues have driven the GUI testing problem domain towards automation.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Many different techniques have been proposed to automatically generate test suites that are complete and that simulate user behavior.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Most of the testing techniques attempt to build on those previously used to test CLI programs, but these can have scaling problems when applied to GUIs.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] A novel approach to test suite generation, adapted from a CLI technique involves using a planning system.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Planning systems determine a path from the initial state to the goal state by using the operators.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] As a simple example of a planning problem, given two words and a single operation which replaces a single letter in a word with another, the goal might be to change one word into another.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] In the authors used the planner IPP to demonstrate this technique.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The system's UI is first analyzed to determine the possible operations.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] These become the operators used in the planning problem.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Next an initial system state is determined, and a goal state is specified that the tester feels would allow exercising of the system.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The planning system determines a path from the initial state to the goal state, which becomes the test plan.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Using a planner to generate the test cases has some specific advantages over manual generation.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] A planning system pays attention to order.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Often to test a certain function, the test case must be complex and follow a path through the GUI where the operations are performed in a specific order.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] When done manually, this can lead to errors and also can be quite difficult and time-consuming to do.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Finally, and most importantly, a planning system is goal oriented.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The tester is focusing test suite generation on what is most important, testing the functionality of the system.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] When manually creating a test suite, the tester is more focused on how to test a function (i. e. the specific path through the GUI).
[src:autoit/gui-testing] By using a planning system, the path is taken care of and the tester can focus on what function to test.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] An additional benefit of this is that a planning system is not restricted in any way when generating the path and may often find a path that was never anticipated by the tester.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This problem is a very important one to combat.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Another method of generating GUI test cases simulates a novice user.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] An expert user of a system tends to follow a direct and predictable path through a GUI, whereas a novice user would follow a more random path.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] A novice user is then likely to explore more possible states of the GUI than an expert.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The difficulty lies in generating test suites that simulate 'novice' system usage.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Using genetic algorithms have been proposed to solve this problem.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Novice paths through the system are not random paths.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] First, a novice user will learn over time and generally would not make the same mistakes repeatedly, and, secondly, a novice user is following a plan and probably has some domain or system knowledge.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Genetic algorithms work as follows: a set of 'genes' are created randomly and then are subjected to some task.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The genes that complete the task best are kept and the ones that do not are discarded.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The process is again repeated with the surviving genes being replicated and the rest of the set filled in with more random genes.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Eventually one gene (or a small set of genes if there is some threshold set) will be the only gene in the set and is naturally the best fit for the given problem.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] In the case of GUI testing, the method works as follows.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Each gene is essentially a list of random integer values of some fixed length.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Each of these genes represents a path through the GUI.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The success of the genes are scored by a criterion that rewards the best 'novice' behavior.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] A system to perform GUI testing for the X window system, extensible to any windowing system, was introduced by Kasik and George.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The X Window system provides functionality (via XServer and its protocol) to dynamically send GUI input to and get GUI output from the program without directly using the GUI.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] For example, one can call XSendEvent() to simulate a click on a pull-down menu, and so forth.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This system allows researchers to automate the test case generation and testing for any given application under test, in such a way that a set of novice user test cases can be created.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] At first the strategies were migrated and adapted from the CLI testing strategies.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] A popular method used in the CLI environment is capture/playback.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Capture playback is a system where the system screen is "captured" as a bitmapped graphic at various times during system testing.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This capturing allowed the tester to "play back" the testing process and compare the screens at the output phase of the test with expected screens.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This validation could be automated since the screens would be identical if the case passed and different if the case failed.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Using capture/playback worked quite well in the CLI world but there are significant problems when one tries to implement it on a GUI-based system.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] The most obvious problem one finds is that the screen in a GUI system may look different while the state of the underlying system is the same, making automated validation extremely difficult.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This is because a GUI allows graphical objects to vary in appearance and placement on the screen.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Fonts may be different, window colors or sizes may vary but the system output is basically the same.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This would be obvious to a user, but not obvious to an automated validation system.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] To combat this and other problems, testers have gone 'under the hood' and collected GUI interaction data from the underlying windowing system.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] By capturing the window 'events' into logs the interactions with the system are now in a format that is decoupled from the appearance of the GUI.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Now, only the event streams are captured.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] There is some filtering of the event streams necessary since the streams of events are usually very detailed and most events are not directly relevant to the problem.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This approach can be made easier by using an MVC architecture for example and making the view (i. e. the GUI here) as simple as possible while the model and the controller hold all the logic.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Another approach is to use the software's built-in assistive technology, to use an HTML interface or a three-tier architecture that makes it also possible to better separate the user interface from the rest of the application.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] Another way to run tests on a GUI is to build a driver into the GUI so that commands or events can be sent to the software from another program.
[src:autoit/gui-testing] This method of directly sending events to and receiving events from a system is highly desirable when testing, since the input and output testing can be fully automated and user error is eliminated.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:autoit/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:autoit/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:autoit/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:autoit/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:autoit/windows] The first version of Windows, Windows 1.0, was released on November 20, 1985 as a graphical operating system shell for MS-DOS in response to growing interest in graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:autoit/windows] The name *Windows* is a reference to the windowing system in GUIs.
[src:autoit/windows] The 1990 release of Windows 3.0 catapulted its market success and led to the launch of various other product families, including the (now-defunct) Windows Mobile, Windows Phone, and Windows CE/Embedded Compact.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows is the most popular desktop operating system in the world, with a 72% market share as of June 2026, and the second-most popular operating system overall, behind Android.
[src:autoit/windows] As of June 2026, Windows 11 is the most used desktop version of Windows, with a market share of 70%.
[src:autoit/windows] All members of the Windows product family are, as of 2026, based on Windows NT.
[src:autoit/windows] The first version of Windows in that product line, Windows NT 3.1, was intended for server computing and corporate workstations.
[src:autoit/windows] It now consists of four sub-families that tend to be released almost simultaneously and share the same kernel.
[src:autoit/windows] The term *Windows* collectively describes any or all of several generations of Microsoft operating system products.
[src:autoit/windows] The history of Windows dates back to 1981 when Microsoft started work on a program called "Interface Manager".
[src:autoit/windows] The name "Windows" comes from the fact that the system was one of the first to use graphical boxes to represent programs; in the industry, at the time, these were called "windows" and the underlying software was called "windowing software".
[src:autoit/windows] It was announced in November 1983 (after the Apple Lisa, but before the Macintosh) under the name "Windows", but Windows 1.0 was not released until November 1985.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 1.0 was to compete with Apple's operating system, but achieved little popularity.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 1.0 is not a complete operating system; rather, it extends MS-DOS.
[src:autoit/windows] The shell of Windows 1.0 is a program known as the MS-DOS Executive.
[src:autoit/windows] Components included Calculator, Calendar, Cardfile, Clipboard Viewer, Clock, Control Panel, Notepad, Paint, Reversi, Terminal and Write.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 1.0 does not allow overlapping windows.
[src:autoit/windows] Only modal dialog boxes may appear over other windows.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft sold as included Windows Development libraries with the C development environment, which included numerous windows samples.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 2.0 was released in December 1987, and was more popular than its predecessor.
[src:autoit/windows] It features several improvements to the user interface and memory management.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 2.03 changed the OS from tiled windows to overlapping windows.
[src:autoit/windows] The result of this change led to Apple Computer filing a suit against Microsoft alleging infringement on Apple's copyrights (eventually settled in court in Microsoft's favor in 1993).
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 2.0 also introduced more sophisticated keyboard shortcuts and could make use of expanded memory.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 2.1 was released in two different versions: Windows/286 and Windows/386.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows/386 uses the virtual 8086 mode of the Intel 80386 to multitask several DOS programs and the paged memory model to emulate expanded memory using available extended memory.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows/286, in spite of its name, runs on both Intel 8086 and Intel 80286 processors.
[src:autoit/windows] It runs in real mode but can make use of the high memory area.
[src:autoit/windows] In addition to full Windows packages, there were runtime-only versions that shipped with early Windows software from third parties and made it possible to run their Windows software on MS-DOS and without the full Windows feature set.
[src:autoit/windows] The early versions of Windows are often thought of as graphical shells, mostly because they ran on top of MS-DOS and used it for file system services.
[src:autoit/windows] However, even the earliest Windows versions already assumed many typical operating system functions; notably, having their own executable file format and providing their own device drivers (timer, graphics, printer, mouse, keyboard and sound).
[src:autoit/windows] Unlike MS-DOS, Windows allowed users to execute multiple graphical applications at the same time, through cooperative multitasking.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 3.0, released in 1990, improved the design, mostly because of virtual memory and loadable virtual device drivers (VxDs) that allow Windows to share arbitrary devices between multi-tasked DOS applications.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 3.0 applications can run in protected mode, which gives them access to several megabytes of memory without the obligation to participate in the software virtual memory scheme.
[src:autoit/windows] They run inside the same address space, where the segmented memory provides a degree of protection.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 3.0 also featured improvements to the user interface.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft rewrote critical operations from C into assembly.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 3.0 was the first version of Windows to achieve broad commercial success, selling 2 million copies in the first six months.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 3.1, made generally available on March 1, 1992, featured a facelift.
[src:autoit/windows] In October 1992, Windows for Workgroups, a special version with integrated peer-to-peer networking features, was released.
[src:autoit/windows] Support for Windows 3.1 ended on December 31, 2001.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 3.2, released in 1994, is an updated version of the Chinese version of Windows 3.1.
[src:autoit/windows] The update was limited to this language version, as it fixed only issues related to the complex writing system of the Chinese language.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 3.2 was generally sold by computer manufacturers with a ten-disk version of MS-DOS that also had Simplified Chinese characters in basic output and some translated utilities.
[src:autoit/windows] The next major consumer-oriented release of Windows, Windows 95, was released on August 24, 1995.
[src:autoit/windows] While still remaining MS-DOS-based, Windows 95 introduced support for native 32-bit applications, plug and play hardware, preemptive multitasking, long file names of up to 255 characters, and provided increased stability over its predecessors.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 95 also introduced a redesigned, object oriented user interface, replacing the previous Program Manager with the Start menu, taskbar, and Windows Explorer shell.
[src:autoit/windows] The first OSR of Windows 95 was also the first version of Windows to be bundled with Microsoft's web browser, Internet Explorer.
[src:autoit/windows] Mainstream support for Windows 95 ended on December 31, 2000, and extended support for Windows 95 ended on December 31, 2001.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 95 was followed up with the release of Windows 98 on June 25, 1998, which introduced the Windows Driver Model, support for USB composite devices, support for ACPI, hibernation, and support for multi-monitor configurations.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 98 also included integration with Internet Explorer 4 through Active Desktop and other aspects of the Windows Desktop Update (a series of enhancements to the Explorer shell which was also made available for Windows 95).
[src:autoit/windows] In June 1999, Microsoft released Windows 98 Second Edition, an updated version of Windows 98.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 98 SE added Internet Explorer 5.0 and Windows Media Player 6.2 amongst other upgrades.
[src:autoit/windows] Mainstream support for Windows 98 ended on June 30, 2002, and extended support for Windows 98 ended on July 11, 2006.
[src:autoit/windows] On September 14, 2000, Microsoft released Windows Me (Millennium Edition), the last DOS-based version of Windows.
[src:autoit/windows] However, Windows Me was faced with criticism for its speed and instability, along with hardware compatibility issues and its removal of real mode DOS support.
[src:autoit/windows] *PC World* considered Windows Me to be one of the worst operating systems Microsoft had ever released, and the fourth worst tech product of all time.
[src:autoit/windows] In November 1988, a new development team within Microsoft (which included former Digital Equipment Corporation developers Dave Cutler and Mark Lucovsky) began work on a revamped version of IBM and Microsoft's OS/2 operating system known as "NT OS/2".
[src:autoit/windows] NT OS/2 was intended to be a secure, multi-user operating system with POSIX compatibility and a modular, portable kernel with preemptive multitasking and support for multiple processor architectures.
[src:autoit/windows] However, following the successful release of Windows 3.0, the NT development team decided to rework the project to use an extended 32-bit port of the Windows API known as Win32 instead of those of OS/2.
[src:autoit/windows] Win32 maintained a similar structure to the Windows APIs (allowing existing Windows applications to easily be ported to the platform), but also supported the capabilities of the existing NT kernel.
[src:autoit/windows] Following its approval by Microsoft's staff, development continued on what was now Windows NT, the first 32-bit version of Windows.
[src:autoit/windows] However, IBM objected to the changes, and ultimately continued OS/2 development on its own.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows NT was the first Windows operating system based on a hybrid kernel.
[src:autoit/windows] The hybrid kernel was designed as a modified microkernel, influenced by the Mach microkernel developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, but without meeting all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:autoit/windows] The first release of the resulting operating system, Windows NT 3.1 (named to associate it with Windows 3.1) was released in July 1993, with versions for desktop workstations and servers.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows NT 3.5 was released in September 1994, focusing on performance improvements and support for Novell's NetWare, and was followed up by Windows NT 3.51 in May 1995, which included additional improvements and support for the PowerPC architecture.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows NT 4.0 was released in June 1996, introducing the redesigned interface of Windows 95 to the NT series.
[src:autoit/windows] On February 17, 2000, Microsoft released Windows 2000, a successor to NT 4.0.
[src:autoit/windows] The Windows NT name was dropped at this point in order to put a greater focus on the Windows brand.
[src:autoit/windows] The next major version of Windows NT, Windows XP, was released to manufacturing (RTM) on August 24, 2001, and to the general public on October 25, 2001.
[src:autoit/windows] The introduction of Windows XP aimed to unify the consumer-oriented Windows 9x series with the architecture introduced by Windows NT, a change which Microsoft promised would provide better performance over its DOS-based predecessors.
[src:autoit/windows] At retail, Windows XP was marketed in two main editions: the "Home" edition was targeted towards consumers, while the "Professional" edition was targeted towards business environments and power users, and included additional security and networking features.
[src:autoit/windows] Mainstream support for Windows XP ended on April 14, 2009.
[src:autoit/windows] Extended support ended on April 8, 2014.
[src:autoit/windows] After Windows 2000, Microsoft also changed its release schedules for server operating systems; the server counterpart of Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, was released in April 2003.
[src:autoit/windows] It was followed in March 2006, by Windows Server 2003 R2.
[src:autoit/windows] After a lengthy development process, Windows Vista was released only for volume licensing on November 30, 2006, and finally, on January 30, 2007, it was officially released to everyone, including consumers.
[src:autoit/windows] It contained a number of new features, from a redesigned shell and user interface to significant technical changes, with a particular focus on security features.
[src:autoit/windows] It was available in a number of different editions, and has been subject to some criticism, such as drop of performance, longer boot time, criticism of new UAC, and stricter license agreement.
[src:autoit/windows] Vista's server counterpart, Windows Server 2008 was released in early 2008.
[src:autoit/windows] On July 22, 2009, Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 were released to manufacturing (RTM) and were officially released, including for the public, months later on October 22, 2009.
[src:autoit/windows] Unlike its predecessor, Windows Vista, which introduced a large number of new features, Windows 7 was intended to be a more focused, incremental upgrade to the Windows line, with the goal of being compatible with applications and hardware with which Windows Vista was already compatible.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 8, the successor to Windows 7, was released generally on October 26, 2012.
[src:autoit/windows] A number of significant changes were made on Windows 8, including the introduction of a user interface based around Microsoft's Metro design language with optimizations for touch-based devices such as tablets and all-in-one PCs.
[src:autoit/windows] These changes include the Start screen, which uses large tiles that are more convenient for touch interactions and allow for the display of continually updated information, and a new class of apps which are designed primarily for use on touch-based devices.
[src:autoit/windows] The new Windows version required a minimum resolution of 1024×768 pixels, effectively making it unfit for netbooks with 800×600-pixel screens.
[src:autoit/windows] An update to Windows 8, called Windows 8.1, was released on October 17, 2013, and includes features such as new live tile sizes, deeper OneDrive integration, and many other revisions.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 8 and Windows 8.1 have been subject to some criticism, such as the removal of the Start menu.
[src:autoit/windows] On September 30, 2014, Microsoft announced Windows 10 as the successor to Windows 8.1.
[src:autoit/windows] It was released on July 29, 2015, and addresses shortcomings in the user interface first introduced with Windows 8.
[src:autoit/windows] Changes on PC include the return of the Start Menu, a virtual desktop system, and the ability to run Windows Store apps within windows on the desktop rather than in full-screen mode.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 10 is said to be available to update from qualified Windows 7 with SP1, Windows 8.1 and Windows Phone 8.1 devices from the Get Windows 10 Application (for Windows 7, Windows 8.1) or Windows Update (Windows 7).
[src:autoit/windows] In February 2017, Microsoft announced the migration of its Windows source code repository from Perforce to Git.
[src:autoit/windows] This migration involved 3.5 million separate files in a 300-gigabyte repository.
[src:autoit/windows] By May 2017, 90 percent of its engineering team was using Git, in about 8500 commits and 1760 Windows builds per day.
[src:autoit/windows] In June 2021, shortly before Microsoft's announcement of Windows 11, Microsoft updated their lifecycle policy pages for Windows 10, revealing that support for their last release of Windows 10 will end on October 14, 2025.
[src:autoit/windows] On April 27, 2023, Microsoft announced that version 22H2 would be the last of Windows 10.
[src:autoit/windows] On June 24, 2021, Windows 11 was announced as the successor to Windows 10 during a livestream.
[src:autoit/windows] The new operating system was designed to be more user-friendly and understandable.
[src:autoit/windows] As of May 2022, Windows 11 is a free upgrade to Windows 10 users who meet the system requirements.
[src:autoit/windows] In July 2021, Microsoft announced it will start selling subscriptions to virtualized Windows desktops as part of a new *Windows 365* service in the following month.
[src:autoit/windows] The new service will allow for cross-platform usage, aiming to make the operating system available for both Apple and Android users.
[src:autoit/windows] It is a separate service and offers several variations including Windows 365 Frontline, Windows 365 Boot, and the Windows 365 app.
[src:autoit/windows] The subscription service will be accessible through any operating system with a web browser.
[src:autoit/windows] The new service is an attempt at capitalizing on the growing trend, fostered during the COVID-19 pandemic, for businesses to adopt a hybrid remote work environment, in which "employees split their time between the office and home".
[src:autoit/windows] As the service will be accessible through web browsers, Microsoft will be able to bypass the need to publish the service through Google Play or the Apple App Store.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft announced Windows 365 availability to business and enterprise customers on August 2, 2021.
[src:autoit/windows] Multilingual support has been built into Windows since Windows 3.0.
[src:autoit/windows] The language for both the keyboard and the interface can be changed through the Region and Language Control Panel.
[src:autoit/windows] Third-party IMEs may also be installed if a user feels that the provided one is insufficient for their needs.
[src:autoit/windows] Since Windows 2000, English editions of Windows NT have East Asian IMEs (such as Microsoft Pinyin IME and Microsoft Japanese IME) bundled, but files for East Asian languages may be manually installed on Control Panel.
[src:autoit/windows] Interface languages for the operating system are free for download, but some languages are limited to certain editions of Windows.
[src:autoit/windows] This is used for most languages in emerging markets.
[src:autoit/windows] Full Language Packs, which translate the complete operating system, are only available for specific editions of Windows (Ultimate and Enterprise editions of Windows Vista and 7, and all editions of Windows 8, 8.1 and RT except Single Language).
[src:autoit/windows] They do not require a specific base language and are commonly used for more popular languages such as French or Chinese.
[src:autoit/windows] These languages cannot be downloaded through the Download Center, but are available as optional updates through the Windows Update service (except Windows 8).
[src:autoit/windows] The interface language of installed applications is not affected by changes in the Windows interface language.
[src:autoit/windows] The availability of languages depends on the application developers themselves.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012 introduce a new Language Control Panel where both the interface and input languages can be simultaneously changed, and language packs, regardless of type, can be downloaded from a central location.
[src:autoit/windows] The PC Settings app in Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2 also includes a counterpart settings page for this.
[src:autoit/windows] Changing the interface language also changes the language of preinstalled Windows Store apps (such as Mail, Maps and News) and certain other Microsoft-developed apps (such as Remote Desktop).
[src:autoit/windows] The above limitations for language packs are however still in effect, except that full language packs can be installed for any edition except Single Language, which caters to emerging markets.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows NT included support for several platforms before the x86-based personal computer became dominant in the professional world.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows NT 4.0 and its predecessors supported PowerPC, DEC Alpha and MIPS R4000 (although some of the platforms implement 64-bit computing, the OS treated them as 32-bit).
[src:autoit/windows] Windows 2000 dropped support for all platforms, except the third generation x86 (known as IA-32) or newer in 32-bit mode.
[src:autoit/windows] The client line of the Windows NT family still ran on IA-32 up to Windows 10 (the server line of the Windows NT family still ran on IA-32 up to Windows Server 2008).
[src:autoit/windows] With the introduction of the Intel Itanium architecture (IA-64), Microsoft released new versions of Windows to support it.
[src:autoit/windows] Itanium versions of Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 were released at the same time as their mainstream x86 counterparts.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows XP 64-Bit Edition (Version 2003), released in 2003, is the last Windows client operating system to support Itanium.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows Server line continues to support this platform until Windows Server 2012; Windows Server 2008 R2 is the last Windows operating system to support Itanium architecture.
[src:autoit/windows] On April 25, 2005, Microsoft released Windows XP Professional x64 Edition and Windows Server 2003 x64 editions to support x86-64 (or simply x64), the 64-bit version of x86 architecture.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows Vista was the first client version of Windows NT to be released simultaneously in IA-32 and x64 editions.
[src:autoit/windows] An edition of Windows 8 known as Windows RT was specifically created for computers with ARM architecture, and while ARM is still used for Windows smartphones with Windows 10, tablets with Windows RT will not be updated.
[src:autoit/windows] Starting from Windows 10 Fall Creators Update (version 1709) and later includes support for ARM-based PCs.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows CE (officially known as *Windows Embedded Compact*), is an edition of Windows that runs on minimalistic computers, like satellite navigation systems and some mobile phones.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows Embedded Compact is based on its own dedicated kernel, dubbed Windows CE kernel.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft licenses Windows CE to OEMs and device makers.
[src:autoit/windows] The OEMs and device makers can modify and create their own user interfaces and experiences, while Windows CE provides the technical foundation to do so.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows CE was used in the Dreamcast along with Sega's own proprietary OS for the console.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows CE was the core from which Windows Mobile was derived.
[src:autoit/windows] Its successor, Windows Phone 7, was based on components from both Windows CE 6.0 R3 and Windows CE 7.0.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows Phone 8 however, is based on the same NT-kernel as Windows 8.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows Embedded Compact is not to be confused with Windows XP Embedded or Windows NT 4.0 Embedded, modular editions of Windows based on Windows NT kernel.
[src:autoit/windows] Xbox OS is an unofficial name given to the version of Windows that runs on Xbox consoles.
[src:autoit/windows] From Xbox One onwards it is an implementation with an emphasis on virtualization (using Hyper-V) as it is three operating systems running at once, consisting of the core operating system, a second implemented for games and a more Windows-like environment for applications.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft updates Xbox One's OS every month, and these updates can be downloaded from the Xbox Live service to the Xbox and subsequently installed, or by using offline recovery images downloaded via a PC.
[src:autoit/windows] It was originally based on NT 6.2 (Windows 8) kernel, and the latest version runs on an NT 10.0 base.
[src:autoit/windows] This system is sometimes referred to as "Windows 10 on Xbox One".
[src:autoit/windows] Xbox One and Xbox Series operating systems also allow limited (due to licensing restrictions and testing resources) backward compatibility with previous generation hardware, and the Xbox 360's system is backwards compatible with the original Xbox.
[src:autoit/windows] Up to and including every version before Windows 2000, Microsoft used an in-house version control system named Source Library Manager (SLM).
[src:autoit/windows] Shortly after Windows 2000 was released, Microsoft switched to a fork of Perforce named Source Depot.
[src:autoit/windows] This system was used up until 2017 when the system could not keep up with the size of Windows.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft had begun to integrate Git into Team Foundation Server in 2013, but Windows (and Office) continued to rely on Source Depot.
[src:autoit/windows] The Windows code in Source Depot was divided among 65 different repositories.
[src:autoit/windows] In 2017 Microsoft announced that it would start using Git, an open source version control system created by Linus Torvalds, and in May 2017 they reported that the migration into a new Git repository was complete.
[src:autoit/windows] Each Git repository contains a complete history of all the files, which tends to be very large for Windows.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft has been working on a new project called the Virtual File System for Git (VFSForGit) to address these challenges.
[src:autoit/windows] In 2021 the VFS for Git was superseded by **Scalar**.
[src:autoit/windows] Use of Windows 10 has exceeded Windows 7 globally since early 2018.
[src:autoit/windows] Those statistics do not include servers (including cloud computing, where Linux has significantly more market share than Windows) as Net Applications and StatCounter use web browsing as a proxy for all use.
[src:autoit/windows] While the Windows 9x series offered the option of having profiles for multiple users with separate profiles and home folders, it had no concept of access privileges, allowing any user to edit others' files.
[src:autoit/windows] In addition, while it ran separate 32-bit applications in separate address spaces, protecting an application's code and data from being read or written by another application, it did not protect the first megabyte of memory from userland applications for compatibility reasons.
[src:autoit/windows] This area of memory contains code critical to the functioning of the operating system, and by writing into this area of memory an application can crash or freeze the operating system.
[src:autoit/windows] This was a source of instability as faulty applications could accidentally write into this region, potentially corrupting important operating system memory, which usually resulted in some form of system error and halt.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows NT was far more secure, implementing access privileges and full memory protection, and, while 32-bit programs meeting the DoD's C2 security rating.
[src:autoit/windows] Prior to Windows Vista, the default user account created during the setup process was an administrator account; the user, and any program the user launched, had full access to the machine.
[src:autoit/windows] Though Windows XP did offer an option of turning administrator accounts into limited accounts, the majority of home users did not do so, partially due to the number of programs which required administrator rights to function properly.
[src:autoit/windows] As a result, most home users still ran as administrator all the time.
[src:autoit/windows] These architectural flaws, combined with Windows's very high popularity, made Windows a frequent target of computer worm and virus writers.
[src:autoit/windows] Furthermore, although Windows NT and its successors are designed for security (including on a network) and multi-user PCs, they were not initially designed with Internet security in mind as much, since, when it was first developed in the early 1990s, Internet use was less prevalent.
[src:autoit/windows] In a 2002 strategy memo entitled "Trustworthy computing" sent to every Microsoft employee, Bill Gates declared that security should become Microsoft's highest priority.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows Vista introduced a privilege elevation system called User Account Control.
[src:autoit/windows] When logging in as a standard user, a logon session is created and a token containing only the most basic privileges is assigned.
[src:autoit/windows] In this way, the new logon session is incapable of making changes that would affect the entire system.
[src:autoit/windows] When logging in as a user in the Administrators group, two separate tokens are assigned.
[src:autoit/windows] The first token contains all privileges typically awarded to an administrator, and the second is a restricted token similar to what a standard user would receive.
[src:autoit/windows] User applications, including the Windows shell, are then started with the restricted token, resulting in a reduced privilege environment even under an Administrator account.
[src:autoit/windows] Leaked documents from 2013 to 2016 codenamed Vault 7 detail the capabilities of the CIA to perform electronic surveillance and cyber warfare, such as the ability to compromise operating systems such as Windows.
[src:autoit/windows] In addition, experts reported a Microsoft security vulnerability, CVE-2019-1162, based on legacy code involving Microsoft CTF and ctfmon (ctfmon.exe), that affects all Windows versions from Windows XP to the then most recent Windows 10 versions; a patch to correct the flaw is available.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft releases security patches through its Windows Update service approximately once a month (usually the second Tuesday of the month), although critical updates are made available at shorter intervals when necessary.
[src:autoit/windows] Versions subsequent to Windows 2000 SP3 and Windows XP implemented automatic download and installation of updates, substantially increasing the number of users installing security updates.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows integrates the Windows Defender antivirus, which is seen as one of the best available.
[src:autoit/windows] Windows also implements Secure Boot, Control Flow Guard, ransomware protection, BitLocker disk encryption, a firewall, and Windows SmartScreen.
[src:autoit/windows] In July 2024, Microsoft signalled an intention to limit kernel access and improve overall security, following a highly publicised CrowdStrike update that caused 8.5 million Windows PCs to crash.
[src:autoit/windows] Part of that initiative is to rewrite parts of Windows in Rust, a memory-safe language.
[src:autoit/windows] In 2025 Microsoft stopped offering support to Window 10 users, including providing security updates.
[src:autoit/windows] Microsoft encouraged people to upgrade to Windows 11 or if this wasn't possible, to sign-up for extended security updates.
[src:autoit/windows] All Windows versions from Windows NT 3 have been based on a file system permission system referred to as AGDLP (Accounts, Global, Domain Local, Permissions) in which file permissions are applied to the file/folder in the form of a 'local group' which then has other 'global groups' as members.
[src:autoit/windows] These global groups then hold other groups or users depending on different Windows versions used.
[src:autoit/windows] This system varies from other vendor products such as Linux and NetWare due to the 'static' allocation of permission being applied directly to the file or folder.
[src:autoit/windows] However using this process of AGLP/AGDLP/AGUDLP allows a small number of static permissions to be applied and allows for easy changes to the account groups without reapplying the file permissions on the files and folders.
[src:autoit/windows] Owing to the operating system's popularity, a number of applications have been released that aim to provide compatibility with Windows applications, either as a compatibility layer for another operating system, or as a standalone system that can run software written for Windows out of the box.
